  en: [
    { question: 'What is the minimum wage in Germany?', answer: 'The statutory minimum wage in Germany is €12.82 per hour as of January 2026, equating to approximately €2,222 per month based on a standard 40-hour working week. Germany introduced its first national minimum wage in 2015 and has raised it multiple times since, with the Federal Minimum Wage Commission reviewing rates annually. Note that some sectors have higher minimum wages under collective agreements.' },
    { question: 'Which EU country has the highest minimum wage?', answer: 'Luxembourg has the highest statutory minimum wage in the European Union at €2,570 per month (gross) as of 2026. This is more than 4 times higher than Bulgaria\'s minimum wage (€551/month). Luxembourg\'s high minimum wage reflects its position as the EU\'s wealthiest country by GDP per capita, dominated by the financial services sector and EU institutional employment.' },
    { question: 'Which EU country has the lowest minimum wage?', answer: 'Bulgaria has the lowest statutory national minimum wage in the EU at approximately €551 per month (BGN 1,077) in 2026. However, it is also one of the fastest-growing — Bulgaria raised its minimum wage by approximately 15% compared to 2025. When adjusted for purchasing power parity, the effective gap between Bulgaria and richer EU states narrows considerably.' },
    { question: 'Does Germany have a minimum wage?', answer: 'Yes. Germany introduced its first statutory national minimum wage of €8.50/hour in January 2015 under the Mindestlohngesetz (Minimum Wage Act). It has been raised multiple times since: €12.00 (Oct 2022), €12.41 (Jan 2024), and €12.82 (Jan 2026). The Federal Minimum Wage Commission (Mindestlohnkommission) reviews and adjusts the rate every two years.' },
    { question: 'Does France have a minimum wage?', answer: 'Yes. France\'s minimum wage is called the SMIC (Salaire Minimum Interprofessionnel de Croissance). In 2026, the SMIC is €11.65/hour or €1,801/month gross. It is automatically adjusted each January 1st and whenever CPI inflation exceeds 2%. France has had a statutory minimum wage since 1970 — one of the longest-running in Europe.' },
    { question: 'Why do Denmark and Sweden have no minimum wage?', answer: 'Denmark, Sweden, and Finland do not have a statutory national minimum wage because their labour markets operate on a different model: strong trade unions and employer associations negotiate sector-level collective agreements that cover the vast majority of workers. In Denmark, these agreements effectively deliver minimum wages of €19–21/hour in most sectors — significantly higher than many countries with statutory minimums. The EU Minimum Wage Directive (2022) does not require member states with high collective bargaining coverage to adopt a statutory minimum.' },
    { question: 'What is the minimum wage in Spain?', answer: 'Spain\'s minimum wage (Salario Mínimo Interprofesional, SMI) is €1,184 per month gross in 2026, or €14,208 annually. Spain has dramatically increased its minimum wage in recent years — it stood at €858/month in 2019 and has nearly doubled. Seasonal workers, domestic workers, and some agricultural workers may be covered by different rates under sector agreements.' },
    { question: 'Is minimum wage in Europe enough to live on?', answer: 'It depends heavily on the country. In Luxembourg (€2,570/month), the minimum wage can support a modest but liveable lifestyle given high costs. In Bulgaria (€551/month), local purchasing power means this covers basic expenses in smaller cities despite looking very low in absolute terms. The EU benchmarks a "fair minimum wage" at 60% of the median wage — as of 2026, most EU states with statutory minimums are approaching this target following the 2022 EU Minimum Wage Directive.' },
