  <div class="container page-body">
    <TLDRBox items={fb(tldrItems, lang)} />

    <div class="guide-content">
      <h2>EU Minimum Wages 2026: Complete Data Table</h2>
      <p>The table below lists statutory national minimum wages for all EU member states that have them, sorted from highest to lowest monthly gross amount. Exchange rates for non-euro countries are approximate (April 2026). Countries are linked to their individual minimum wage and salary pages.</p>

      <div class="mw-table-wrapper">
        <table class="mw-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Country</th>
              <th>Monthly (EUR)</th>
              <th>Hourly (EUR)</th>
              <th>vs. 2025</th>
              <th>Notes</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {minWageData.map((row) => {
              const change = row.monthly - row.prevYear;
              const pct = ((change / row.prevYear) * 100).toFixed(1);
              return (
                <tr>
                  <td class="country-cell">
                    <span class="country-flag">{row.flag}</span>
                    <a href={`/${lang}/minimum-wage/${row.code}/`} class="country-link">{row.country}</a>
                  </td>
                  <td class="salary-cell"><strong>€{row.monthly.toLocaleString('en-EU')}</strong></td>
                  <td class="salary-cell secondary">{row.hourly ? `€${row.hourly}` : row.hourlyDisplay}</td>
                  <td class={`change-cell ${change >= 0 ? 'positive' : 'negative'}`}>
                    {change >= 0 ? '+' : ''}{pct}%
                  </td>
                  <td class="note-cell">{row.note}</td>
                </tr>
              );
            })}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p class="data-note">Sources: Official government gazettes, national labour ministries, Eurostat. Monthly figures for hourly-rate countries estimated at 173.33h (40h/week × 52/12). Non-euro figures converted at ECB reference rates (April 2026).</p>

      <h2>Countries Without a Statutory Minimum Wage</h2>
      <p>Six EU member states do not have a statutory national minimum wage. Instead, they rely on sector-level collective bargaining agreements between trade unions and employer organisations. In most cases, effective minimum pay under these agreements is higher than statutory minimums in other EU countries.</p>

      <div class="mw-table-wrapper">
        <table class="mw-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Country</th>
              <th>Minimum Wage Status</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {noMinWageCountries.map((row) => (
              <tr>
                <td class="country-cell">
                  <span class="country-flag">{row.flag}</span>
                  <span class="country-name">{row.country}</span>
                </td>
                <td class="note-cell">{row.note}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h2>Year-over-Year Changes: Who Raised Wages the Most?</h2>
      <p>2026 saw significant minimum wage increases across the EU, driven by the 2022 EU Minimum Wage Directive requiring member states to ensure minimum wages reach at least 60% of the median wage. The fastest-growing minimum wages in 2026:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Bulgaria: +15%</strong> — From ~€477 to €551/month. Still EU's lowest, but fastest-growing as a percentage.</li>
        <li><strong>Lithuania: +6.6%</strong> — From €867 to €924/month; strong wage growth in Baltic region.</li>
        <li><strong>Greece: +6.4%</strong> — From €780 to €830/month; recovering from the decade-long austerity freeze.</li>
        <li><strong>Estonia: +8%</strong> — From €820 to €886/month; Baltic wage convergence continues.</li>
        <li><strong>Netherlands: +11.1%</strong> — From €2,070 to €2,299/month; major reform in 2024 raised the floor significantly.</li>
        <li><strong>Germany: +8.2%</strong> — From €2,054 to €2,222/month; rate set by Mindestlohnkommission (Federal Minimum Wage Commission).</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Cost of Living Context: What Does Minimum Wage Buy?</h2>
      <p>Raw numbers are misleading without purchasing power context. Here's what minimum wage roughly buys in each tier of EU countries:</p>

      <h3>High Minimum Wage Countries (€1,800–€2,570/month)</h3>
      <p><strong>Luxembourg (€2,570):</strong> A single person can afford a one-bedroom apartment (€1,400–1,800/month in Luxembourg City) plus food and transport — but barely. This is why Luxembourg has one of the highest costs of living in the EU. A minimum wage earner may struggle in the capital but live comfortably in peripheral communes.</p>
      <p><strong>Ireland (€2,340), Netherlands (€2,299), Germany (€2,222):</strong> Covers basic housing (shared), food, and transport in most cities, but leaves little margin. In Dublin, Berlin, or Amsterdam specifically, minimum wage is tight. Secondary cities like Limerick, Leipzig, or Eindhoven are much more manageable.</p>
      <p><strong>France (€1,801 SMIC):</strong> Outside Paris, a minimum wage earner can cover rent, food, and transport with some modest savings. In Paris, the SMIC alone is genuinely insufficient for a single person without subsidised housing (HLM).</p>

      <h3>Mid-Range Countries (€800–€1,300/month)</h3>
      <p><strong>Spain (€1,184), Portugal (€870), Greece (€830):</strong> In smaller cities and rural areas, these wages cover a modest lifestyle. In Madrid, Barcelona, Lisbon, or Athens, costs have risen sharply and minimum wage earners typically need social support, family help, or shared housing. Spain's SMI has doubled since 2019, significantly improving living standards.</p>

      <h3>Lower Minimum Wage Countries (€550–€800/month)</h3>
      <p><strong>Bulgaria (€551), Romania (€743), Hungary (€680):</strong> Local purchasing power is far stronger than the euro figure suggests. Rent in Sofia, Bucharest, or Budapest can be €250–450/month outside prime areas. Food and transport are 50–60% cheaper than in Western Europe. A minimum wage earner in Bulgaria can live frugally but adequately — though healthcare, travel, and durables remain challenging on minimum wages.</p>

      <h2>The EU Minimum Wage Directive (2022)</h2>
      <p>In September 2022, the EU adopted the Adequate Minimum Wages Directive, requiring member states to:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Ensure statutory minimum wages are "adequate" — benchmarked at 60% of median gross wage or 50% of average gross wage</li>
        <li>Promote collective bargaining coverage to at least 80% of workers</li>
        <li>Update minimum wages at least every 2 years (or every 4 years for indexed rates)</li>
        <li>Report data annually to the European Labour Authority</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Member states had until November 15, 2024 to transpose the directive. By 2026, most EU countries with statutory minimums have met or are approaching the 60% median benchmark. The directive explicitly does not require countries with high collective bargaining coverage (Denmark, Sweden, Finland, Austria, Italy, Cyprus) to introduce a statutory minimum.</p>

